The Plant does not require its employees to participate in conducting emergency response activities under the HAZWOPER standard; a Non-responding Facility Policy has been adopted for the Plant as a whole.  In the event of an ammonia emergency, the response is to follow the procedures in the Equipment SOP's and the California Hazardous Material Business Plan.  The overall procedure is to shutdown critical systems if it can be done safely by qualified personnel, evacuate, and notify the local response agencies and WPS; WPS employs technicians that are 1910.120(q) Hazardous Material Technician certified.  Plant employees are to implement hazard communications, provide for the safety of visitors and report to the established Evacuation Staging Area(s) for a head count.  Emergency response is coordinated with the City of Oxnard Fire/CUPA.  Oxnard Fire/CUPA has confirmed that the facility is included in the Oxnard Community Emergency Plan required by the Emergency Planning and Community-Right-to-Know Act (EPCRA).    

1.6  Planned changes to improve safety

The primary mechanisms to identify and plan safety improvements include (but are not limited to):
-Process Hazard Analysis revalidation/update;
-Compliance Audits;
-Routine inspections, tests & maintenance (Mechanical Integrity Program);
-IIAR Bulletin 109 Inspections (IIAR minimum safety criteria for the safe operation of ammonia refrigeration process);
-Dandy and WPS Internal Inspection Protocols

The programs above may result in recommendations ranging from capital improvements to routine maintenance of the plant.  Where appropriate service calls are established in parallel to identified needs.  Current planned changes to improve safety include recommendations as a result of the Process Hazard Analysis update performed January 3rd, 2013.  The recommendations have been reviewed by Dandy management and a written implementation schedule has been prepared.  Completion is scheduled by March 29, 201
